  <dsc><c01 id="aspace_109f616ccdc7004ff7e04f26d8fb9d46" level="series"><did><unittitle><extref xlink:href="http://rmc.library.cornell.edu/EAD/pdf_guides/RMM01737.pdf">Link to a copy of the printed finding aid</extref></unittitle></did></c01><c01 audience="internal" id="aspace_470aff55c0b32425f1767bbfeb5c085b" level="series"><did><unittitle>Series I. Correspondence</unittitle></did><scopecontent audience="internal" id="aspace_9731f0cfdddff00cf396edb825c5e502"><head>Scope and Contents</head><p>Box sorted into years and placed in bond paper folders; the letters, money notes, bills, and receipts make up the business and personal correspondence of Wiley H. Scott and his sons Edwin W., Emmet H., and Silas L. Scott.  Concerns various business enterprises which they undertook, such as the "Scott House", a hotel in Nineveh, N.Y., the Scott Brewery in Unadilla, road building in the mid-west, and various legal cases in which they were involved, as a land ejectment suit in Nineveh in 1867, and a contract violation suit in which they were the defendants in 1875.  The Scotts were neighbors of the Hobbs  Family and evidently J.W. Hobbs, acted as their legal counsel.  These papers relating to the Scott family were removed from the Hobbs Bros. Papers (1641) and a few more relative letters are to be found in the post-nineteen hundred correspondence of the collection.</p></scopecontent><c02 audience="internal" id="aspace_f2c0c0dbc23fe940b858bbe64d01e36a" level="file"><did><unittitle>Marriage Certificate</unittitle><unitdate datechar="creation" normal="1861-11-11/1861-11-11" type="inclusive">1861-11-11</unitdate><container id="aspace_9fa878a931df3a4510cab76a317c5e87" label="Mixed Materials [31924064916483]" type="box">1</container></did><scopecontent audience="internal" id="aspace_ccbee83cdb55c81655a363de22b38320"><head>Scope and Contents</head><p>Edwin W. Scott, Nineveh, N.Y. to Abbey F.T Williams, Lansingville</p></scopecontent></c02><c02 audience="internal" id="aspace_8945074cdca1c